					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">My guess is that the A register is being used elsewhere, and that's being affected by the interrupt.<br /><a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/The_frame_and_NMIs#Being_Interrupt-Aware" class="postlink">http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/The_frame_and_NMIs#Being_Interrupt-Aware</a><br /><br />You almost always want to preserve the state of the registers, with code like this in your NMI:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">NMI:<br />&nbsp;pha<br />&nbsp;tya<br />&nbsp;pha<br />&nbsp;txa<br />&nbsp;pha<br /><br />&nbsp;; NMI code here<br /><br />&nbsp;pla<br />&nbsp;tax<br />&nbsp;pla<br />&nbsp;tay<br />&nbsp;pla<br />&nbsp;rti<br /></div></div>

